entry.title: Add Sub-Label to Compact FeatureTiles
entry.content:
Adds sub-label support to compact FeatureTiles. A sub-label can now be

added to a compact tile by setting the sub-label text and updating

the sub-label visibility. By default, the sub-label on compact tiles

will be hidden and need to be manually set to visible after setting the

sub-label text.



If a compact FeatureTile has a sub-label, it only allows one row each

for the primary label and sub-label. By default, compact FeatureTiles

will allow two rows for the primary label as originally designed. If a

user updates the sub-label to be visible on a compact tile, the primary

label and sub-label will be allowed one row of text each.

entry.title: iwa: Wait for ongoing updates to complete before serving requests
entry.content:
If an update is in the process of being applied, pause all requests to

the IWA until the update is applied. There are two cases where this is

relevant:

- Normally, we wait for all windows of an IWA to close, and only then

kick-off the update apply process. However, if the user were to

re-open an IWA window during the update apply process, we need to

delay loading of the window contents until after the update has

finished applying.

- On startup, if updates from the previous browser session are still

pending (possibly because the user never closed the windows of the

IWA), then we queue the pending updates to be applied. However, if

either the user or the browser opens an IWA window while we apply

updates, we need to wait for that to finish, similar to the case

above.

entry.title: Only consider reference box zoom when applying clip-path
entry.content:
Clip-paths use a reference box which may or may not include zoom (to

handle html and svg contexts). The clip-path implementation is

recursive, to support clip-paths on clip-paths, and was incorrectly

using the current clip-path object for adjusting the reference box's

zoom. This patch separately tracks both the current clip path owner

object and the reference box object, and only uses the latter for zoom.

This fixes a hit testing regression from https://crrev.com/1185100, as

well as a pre-existing rendering bug (tests added for each).

entry.title: Add unit-tests for closing quic session and posting migration right after
entry.content:
* Connection Migration has a different operation mode when closing

connection unlike the usual. It depends on `closeSessionOnErrorLater` which

will close the session(but not call the destructor) then post a task to destroy

the session. This has introduced race conditions and plenty of bugs for Cronet / Clank.



* This CL just adds unit-tests which exhibits the same behavior by calling `closeSessionOnErrorLater`

explicitly then calling `migrateToSocket` which replicates the latest crash that happened on Cronet.



* Added another unit-test that replicates the crash but from a different position where `FinishMigrate` is called

just after `closeSessionOnErrorLater`.



* This is just another patch for the `closeSessionOnErrorLater` disaster, I will follow-up with some CLs

to migrate to closeSessionOnError.



* In an Ideal world, we should not be using CloseSessionOnErrorLater as it

introduces a window for race conditions to happen. We should be using

CloseSessionOnError as this will guarantee that no other callback can be

executed after the session has been closed.

entry.title: media/gpu/test: Fix H.264 NALU boundary detection
entry.content:
video_decode_accelerator_(perf_)test's EncodedDataHelper is used for

reading H.264 (and other codecs ofc) bitstreams frames from disk. To

find the NALU boundary, it looks for the marker 0x00 00 00 01; however,

NALUs can also be marked by 0x00 00 01 (*); this CL fixes this.



This situation was found during V4L2StatefulVideoDecoder bringup: it

was observed that said decoder was fed very large media::DecoderBuffers

for some H.264 specific "main" test vectors (e.g. CAPCM1_Sand_E.h264)

and this was traced down to EncodedDataHelper not reading one NALU at

a time from disk, but bundling very many at once.



With this CL, all H.264 main test vectors verify MD5Sums on trogdor

_except_ for CVPCMNL2_SVA_C.h264 (argh! :).



(*) This is described in the spec but a quick search gives as well e.g.

https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/directshow/h-264-video-types#h264-bitstream-with-start-codes

entry.title: Remove Form Card Matching In Mandatory Reauth Opt-In Flow (CL 1 of 3)
entry.content:
The old behavior here was that if the user autofilled a card via non-

interactive authentication (green path), and then deleted the card in

the form and manually typed in a different card, we would do a matching

check to make sure that the card in the form matched the most recently

filled card before we offer re-auth opt-in.



With this CL, we will remove the matching check. Instead, with this CL,

we will offer re-auth opt-in if the user's most recent autofill moment

was a non-interactive authentication (green path).



The difference in functionality with this CL will be that in the case

where a user green paths a card, then deletes the card and manually

types in a different card in the form, we will now offer re-auth opt-in.

Before this CL, in this scenario, we would not offer re-auth opt-in.



After discussing this case within engineering and with product, we

realized that it is an extremely rare edge cased based on the UMA data.

Handling it adds a lot of complexity in the code, and not offering re-

auth opt-in might actually not be the ideal user journey from a product

perspective. It is possible if a user went through non-interactive

authentication but then manually typed in a different card, they

actually disliked the non-interactive authentication and wanted to use a

different card. Offering to always authenticate can actually make a lot

of sense in this use-case.



CL #2 in this chain will update the associated histograms and enums to

match this refactor.



CL #3 in this chain will move the class variable that denotes the most

recent payments autofill was a non-interactive authentication into

CreditCardAccessManager.
